forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tudenham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Tuddenham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tuddenham","meanings":["English: locative name, principally from from East or West Tuddenham (Norfolk), but also from Tuddenham (Suffolk) or Tuddenham Saint Martin (Suffolk)."]}]},{"name":"Willaim","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Willaim de Tudenham was born about 1170, in Oxborough, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de Tudenham, was 28 and his mother, Maud Glanville, was 25. He married Basil de Wramplingham about 1202, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1170–":"umbes 1170–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1171–Male":"1171–Surnud","1173–1173":"1173–1173","1176–1207":"1176–1207","1203–Male":"1203–Surnud",